
Thanks for your prayers.

The procedure went well, and I’m doing well. We won't know results for a week or two. They decided not to place a stent until they have the results from the biopsy.

Kathy and I drove to the hospital, they had me keep my pants and shoes on, swapping my shirt for a hospital gown.  I followed the nurse to the procedure room and lay down on a table. Then they asked me questions to make sure I understood what they were doing and why.  They hooked up an IV drip to my port then gave me fentanyl (for pain) and Versed (to keep me calm and relaxed during the procedure).

They slid a thin tube down through the big vein in my neck into the veins near my liver and pancreas, using it as a pathway to guide a biopsy needle to the right spot. The doctors used ultrasound from inside the veins and X-ray pictures to steer everything safely. That way, they could see the area around the portal vein, which sits right next to the pancreas.

Once they had the right angle, they used the needle to take several tiny core samples of tissue from the area around the portal vein (where the concern is). A lab specialist checked each sample under a microscope to make sure the samples were good. If not, they would have been able to take extra samples then and there.

Kathy joined me in the recovery room. They offered me apple chips and Tillamook cheddar cheese, which was really quite nice, especially since I hadn't been able to eat breakfast or lunch because of the procedure.

We went home, ate lunch, and I went down for a nap.  And now we wait for the results.

Whatever happens, it is all in God's good hands.  And we continue to appreciate your prayers.

